        <p>Multiply your total weekly decimal hours by your hourly rate. If you worked overtime (typically over 40 hours in a week), multiply those extra hours by your overtime rate (usually 1.5 times your regular rate) and add it to your regular pay.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the rules for unpaid breaks?</summary>
        <p>Under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), short breaks (usually 20 minutes or less) must be paid. Bona fide meal periods (typically 30 minutes or more) where you are completely relieved from duty are generally unpaid.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I convert minutes to decimal hours?</summary>
        <p>Divide the number of minutes by 60. For example, 15 minutes is 0.25 hours (15/60), 30 minutes is 0.5 hours (30/60), and 45 minutes is 0.75 hours (45/60).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Should time sheets be rounded?</summary>
        <p>Yes, employers can round time under the FLSA, usually to the nearest 5, 10, or 15 minutes, provided the rounding doesn't consistently favor the employer. However, exact tracking is often preferred to avoid wage disputes.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
